<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-121-804  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 121 804.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Information Week  March 6 1989 n210 p41(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Census tamed with Tiger. (US Bureau of the Census) (TopologicallyIntegrated Geographic Encoding and Referencing)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Forsythe, Jason.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The US Bureau of the Census has finished its first computer map ofthe US and its territories.andP;  The world's first national digitalmap, the Topologically Integrated Geographic Encoding andReferencing, nicknamed Tiger, is the largest known commercialdatabase in the world, with around 50-70 gigabytes of data.andP;  The$200 million map project was spurred by complaints from users ofCensus Bureau information from the 1980 census.andP;  It was estimatedthat over 3 million people were missed during that count.andP;  The newstandardized digital maps will eliminate errors that resulted frominaccurate and inconsistent hand-drafted maps.andP;  Another advantageis that Tiger maps can be customized to suit the detail or scaleneeded by the user.andP;  The map is expected to save $50 millionduring the 2000 census.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     United States. Bureau of the CensusDigital ComputersMapsCensusAutomationGovernment AgencyData Bases.andO;Feature:   illustrationphotograph.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>